<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-274-599  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 274 599.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Jan 23 1989 n297 p83(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>StarLAN, StarMail ease health-care conglomerate's woes.andO;(Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center in Chicago)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Communication problems at the Rush-Presbyterian-St.andP;  Luke'sMedical Center are being solved by the installation of an ATandamp;TStarLAN network and PMX StarMail electronic mail system.andP;  Thehealth-care conglomerate includes 22 buildings over 33 acres andhas a wide variety of computing equipment.andP;  A project, called thePatient Care Information System (PCIS), is underway to connectthis diverse equipment, but implementation is difficult because ofthe diverse equipment and the fact that PCIS project group staffand PCIS users are not in the same building.andP;  The StarLAN networkconnects 80 Compaq Computer Corp, IBM and ATandamp;T microcomputers,enabling PCIS staff and users to use electronic mail fordiscussions, to write and review documentation and to distributedocuments of all kinds.andP;  Future plans call for StarMail to beavailable to 3,000 Rush-Presbyterian employees by the end of 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   AT and T StarMail (Electronic mail system)AT and T Starlan (Local area network).andO;Topic:     Rush Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical CenterHealth CareElectronic Mail SystemsLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>